{"title_page": "Francis Tapon", "text_new": "{{short description|American writer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Francis Tapon\n| image        = Francis Tapon, head shot.jpg\n| caption      = Tapon in 2012\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1970|3|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| nationality  = American, French and Chilean\n|alma_mater = [[Amherst College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])<br />[[Harvard Business School]] ([[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A.]])\n| occupation   = Author, nomad, public speaker, life coach\n| notableworks = ''Hike Your Own Hike''<br/>''The Hidden Europe''\n| website      = {{URL|http://FrancisTapon.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Francis Tapon''' (born March 10, 1970) is an [[author]], [[global nomad]], and [[public speaker]]. He has walked across the United States four times via its [[Triple Crown of Hiking|three major mountain ranges]]. He also walked across Spain twice. He was the first person to do a round-trip backpacking the [[Continental Divide Trail]]. In addition, he [[thru-hike]]d the [[Pacific Crest Trail]] and [[Appalachian Trail]] southbound. He has traveled to over 100 countries of the world.<ref>Krasny, Michael. (December 28, 2011). [http://www.kqed.org/a/forum/R201112291000 \"National radio interview\"]. KQED, San Francisco Public Radio, NPR affiliate. Retrieved November 1, 2013.</ref> Lastly, he is the author of the [[self-help]] travelogue ''Hike Your Own Hike'' and the [[travel narrative]] ''The Hidden Europe: What Eastern Europeans Can Teach Us''.<ref>NTD TV. [http://www.ntdtv.com/xtr/b5/2012/05/08/a697908.html.-%E8%88%8A%E9%87%91%E5%B1%B1%E4%BD%9C%E5%AE%B6%E9%81%8A%E6%9D%B1%E6%AD%90%E7%B1%B2%E6%94%BE%E6%A3%84%E5%85%B1%E7%94%A2%E6%94%BF%E6%AC%8A.html \"Chinese TV interview\"] Retrieved on November 2, 2013</ref> He traveled to all 54 [[African countries]] from 2013 to 2018 and climbed to the highest point of 50 of those countries.<ref>Frank Mallicoat [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_t8Q8pfLxqc \"KPIX CBS affiliate TV interview\"] Dec 18, 2012. Retrieved January 24, 2019.</ref><ref>Tom Stinstra [https://www.sfchronicle.com/sports/article/After-five-years-10-000-miles-in-Africa-Francis-13112246.php] July 29, 2018. Retrieved January 24, 2019.</ref> In 2019, he was inducted into the California Outdoors Hall of Fame.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stienstra |first=Tom |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/outdoors/stienstra/article/California-Outdoors-Hall-of-Fame-inductees-13539700.php |title=California Outdoors Hall of Fame inductees changed landscape |date=January 17, 2019 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n==Early life and career==\nTapon's mother is from [[Chile]] and his father was from [[France]].<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/francis-tapon/ \"Huffington Post bio\"] Retrieved November 1, 2013</ref>\nTapon was born in [[San Francisco]],<ref>[http://www.goodreads.com/author/show/563037.Francis_Tapon/ \"Francis Tapon's biography\"]. Goodreads. Retrieved November 1, 2013.</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Apy1_Q0BI1w \"Interview on French American TV\"] skip to 0:50</ref> where he went to the [[French American International School (San Francisco)|French American International School]] until 10th grade, and then graduated from [[Lick-Wilmerding High School]].\n\nHe earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] [[cum laude]] in [[Religion]] from [[Amherst College]] in 1992.<ref>Lieber, Ben. [https://www.amherst.edu/alumni/learn/bookclub/pastfeatures/november2012] \"Amherst College Alumni Interview\" retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref> He worked in [[Latin America]] for [[Hitachi Data Systems]]. In 1997, he received his [[MBA]] from [[Harvard Business School]].<ref>Tapon, Francis (December 1, 2012) [https://www.alumni.hbs.edu/stories/Pages/story-bulletin.aspx?num=1188 \"The Billion Dollar Question\"]. ''Harvard Business School Bulletin''. Retrieved November 1, 2013.</ref>\n\nAfter [[Harvard]], he co-founded a [[Silicon Valley]] robotic vision company that was covered by [[The New York Times]].<ref>Lewis, Michael (March 1, 1998). [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0CEED8143EF932A35750C0A96E958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=print \"The Little Creepy Crawlers Who Will Eat You In The Night\"]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved November 1, 2013.</ref><ref>Stern, Rachel J. (April 23, 2012) [http://losgatos.patch.com/groups/arts-and-entertainment/p/the-hidden-europe-20-years-after-communism] \"'The Hidden Europe' Comes to Los Gatos\"] Patch.com. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref> Later, he consulted for [[Microsoft]] for 18 months. In 2006, he became a full-time travel writer.<ref>Stienstra, Tom. (February 24, 2008). [http://articles.sfgate.com/2008-02-24/sports/17140081_1_pacific-crest-trail-mexican-border-hike \"His life is a long, gratifying hike\"]. ''San Francisco Chronicle''. Retrieved November 1, 2013.</ref>\n\n==Travels==\n[[File:Francis-Tapon-photo1.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph|Tapon in [[Slovenia]], August 2010]]\nBelow is a chronology of Tapon's most notable travel experiences, which inspired his two books.\n\nIn 2001, he hiked the [[Appalachian Trail]].<ref>Lanza, Michael. (November 2008) [http://www.backpacker.com/november_2008_american_classic_hiking_the_appalachian_trail/destinations/12530?page=3 \"American Classic: Hiking the Appalachian Trail\"]. ''Backpacker Magazine''. Retrieved November 1, 2013.</ref> In 2004, he visited all the countries in [[Eastern Europe]].<ref>Tapon, Francis. (October 5, 2012) [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-2Bd8pNYH8A \"Francis Tapon's TEDx Talk\"]. TEDx Fillmore speech, San Francisco. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref> In 2006, he backpacked the [[Pacific Crest Trail]].<ref>Fulton, Kathryn. (2012) [https://books.google.com/books?id=2QJbyQZHYUYC&pg=PA159&lpg=PA159&dq=francis+tapon+pacific+crest+trail&source=bl&ots=PkTvd75X79&sig=MDiu3X2nl_BXb-2N_z4YAtbaPCQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5JVyUo2DGMqBhAffwYD4Ag&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=francis%20tapon%20pacific%20crest%20trail&f=false ''Hikers' Stories from the Appalachian Trail''], Stackpole Books, page 159. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 2007, he became the first person to walk from [[Mexico]] to [[Canada]] and back to Mexico along the [[Continental Divide Trail]].<ref>Tilin, Andrew. (June 2008) [http://www.backpacker.com/june_2008_feature_onion_mr_magoo_cdt/articles/12430?page=1 \"The Onion vs. Mr. Magoo \u2013 On your mark, get set ... hike. Inside a 5,600-mile footrace on the country's hardest trail.\"]. ''Backpacker Magazine''. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref><ref>M. Biggers, Ashley. (March 2008) \"There & Back Again\", ''New Mexico Magazine''</ref><ref>Bastone, Kelly (August 2008) \"Taking the High Way: Thru-hiking the Continental Divide Trail,\" ''5280'', pp. 70\u201373. Denver magazine reports on Francis Tapon's first-ever yo-yo of the CDT.</ref><ref>Wilt, Bernie. [http://www.practicalbackpacking.com/blog/archives/000035_pbp_episode_31_cdt_yoyo.php \"PBP Episode 31 \u2013 CDT Yo-Yo\"]. PracticalBackpacking.com. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref><ref>Reese, Janet. (19 June 2007). [http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2007/jun/19/5-questions-for-long-distance-hiker-francis/ \"5 questions for long-distance hiker Francis Tapon\"]. ''Rocky Mountain News''. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref>\nThis seven-month journey spanned over 5,600 miles.<ref>Stienstra, Tom. (March 9, 2008). [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/03/09/SPRRVE84U.DTL&hw=tapon&sn=002&sc=096 \"Good time to take inventory on gear \u2013 and yourself\"]. ''San Francisco Chronicle''. . Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref> Francis took the most circuitous, scenic, high, difficult route north and while returning south took the more expedient route on the way down.<ref>Manning, John. (April 8, 2008) [http://www.francistapon.com/images/press/TaponProfileTGO.pdf \"Francis Tapon: The first person to yo-yo America\u2019s wildest trail talks heating, eating and the philosophy of lightweight\"]. ''TGO Magazine''. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref> He hiked [[Ultralight backpacking|ultralight]] since his pack, without food and water, weighed under 6&nbsp;lbs (less than 3&nbsp;kg).<ref>Crooker, Carol. (September 12, 2007) [https://archive.is/20131105173923/http://www.backpackinglight.com/cgi-bin/backpackinglight/podcast_090407_francis_tapon_cdt_yo-yo.html \"Podcast: Francis Tapon is Set to Complete a Backpacking First \u2013 a CDT Yo-Yo\"]. Backpackinglight.com. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref><ref>Stienstra, Tom. (March 9, 2008) [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/03/09/SPRRVE84U.DTL&hw=tapon&sn=002&sc=096 \"Good time to take inventory on gear \u2013 and yourself\"]. ''San Francisco Chronicle''. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref>\n[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]] listed Francis Tapon's round trip on the Continental Divide Trail among one of the most notable feats of 2007.<ref>[http://www.nationalgeographic.com/adventure/best-of-adventure-2008/sports-trends.html \"Best of Adventure, Trends: New Leaf\"] ''National Geographic''. Retrieved November 2, 2012.</ref><ref>Lineback, Neal. (October 1, 2013)  [http://newswatch.nationalgeographic.com/2013/10/19/geography-in-the-news-americas-hiking-trails \"America's Hiking Trails\"] National Geographic: Geography in the News. Retrieved November 2, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he walked across [[Spain]] twice: once by traversing the [[Pyrenees]] from the [[Mediterranean Sea]] to the [[Atlantic Ocean]], and then by hiking [[Way of St. James|El Camino de Santiago]].<ref>Bassets, Marc. (August 17, 2012) [http://francistapon.com/images/travels/spain/La-Vanguardia-17-08-2012.jpg \"El Disidente\"] ''La Vanguardia'' in Spanish. Retrieved November 2, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2008\u20132011, he visited over 40 European countries, including all the Eastern European ones.<ref>Delevett, Peter. (May 19, 2012) [http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/19/business/la-fi-social-travel-20120519/2 \"Social travel' start-ups help travelers gather friends\"] Page 2 of ''Los Angeles Times'' article. Retrieved November 2, 2013</ref><ref>Steves, Rick. (August 17, 2013) [http://www.ricksteves.com/radio/protected/descriptions.cfm?showID=463 \"Bumpy Balkans\"] National Radio Show. Retrieved November 2, 2013</ref><ref>Riddell, Joel. (August 2013)[http://www.newstalk910.com/player/?station=KKSF-AM&program_name=podcast&program_id=diningaround.xml&mid=22190615 \"Dining Around Interview\"] The interview starts at minute 17. NewsTalk 910, KKSF, San Francisco.</ref> He focused on finding Eastern European innovations.<ref>Tapon, Francis. (January 1, 2012) [http://francistapon.com/images/press/WashPost-Innovation.pdf \"Eastern Europe: Innovation's hidden hub\"] ''Washington Post'', page G4. Retrieved November 2. 2013.</ref><ref>Kolawole, Emi. (January 1, 2012) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/innovations/post/europe-the-credit-downgrade-and-what-it-means-for-innovation/2012/01/14/gIQASYJXyP_blog.html \"Europe, the credit downgrade and what it means for innovation\"] WashingtonPost.com. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Steves |first=Rick |url=http://www.ricksteves.com/radio/protected/descriptions.cfm?showID=411 |title=Program 297: Open Phones: Ask Rick; Francis Tapon Explores Eastern Europe |date=August 18, 2012 |access-date=November 1, 2013 |publisher=Rick Steves National Radio Show}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he summed up his travels to date and shared his lessons in his [[TEDx]] talk entitled, \"How and Why Travel Transforms You.\" It has over 100,000 views.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-2Bd8pNYH8A 18-min TEDx video] Retrieved June 3, 2017.</ref> \n\nIn March 2013, he entered Morocco and began a five-year trip to all 54 [[List of sovereign states and dependent territories in Africa|African]] countries. He never left the African continent. Half way through his trip, he met and married a Cameroonian, Rejoice Tapon, who traveled 31 of African countries with him.<ref>[https://francistapon.com/Travels/Africa/Engagement-Taking-the-Plunge How Francis Tapon proposed to Rejoice.] Retrieved April 22, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://francistapon.com/About/Birthday-Wedding-to-Celebrate-Francis-Rejoice-Marriage Francis and Rejoice Tapon marriage] Retrieved April 22, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Tapon returned to a TEDx stage. He had just returned from 5.5 years of nonstop overland travel through all 54 African countries. Tapon shared a story about an African girl who was a \"black sheep\" in her society and what we can learn from it.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PVfADBIsgB8 18-min TEDx video \"Bring Out Your Inner Black Sheep\"] Retrieved May 3, 2019.</ref> \n\nHe returned to the United States in 2018. He plans to write his third book based on the experience. He filmed extensively and has raised over $24,000 to produce a [[Television pilot|pilot TV episode]] by November 2014.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Steves |first=Rick |url=http://www.ricksteves.com/radio/protected/descriptions.cfm?showID=435 |title=Program 314: Travel Portraits; Artist's Safari; Africa 54 |date=February 2, 2013 |access-date=November 1, 2013 |publisher=Rick Steves National Radio Show}}</ref><ref>[https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/ftapon/the-unseen-africa-tv-series-the-pilot-episode-moro Kickstarter Project: The Unseen Africa] Retrieved May 26, 2014</ref> [[Amazon.com]] and [[Lincoln Mercury]] selected him as the best example of someone who is fulfilling the dream of traveling the world.<ref>Amazon.com & Lincoln Mercury did a video profile of people who doing were doing 25 classic dreams [http://www.vimeo.com/718800 Video excerpt of the 'My Dream' campaign] Vimeo.com. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, he was inducted in the California Outdoors Hall of Fame, which includes [[John Muir]] and [[Ansel Adams]].<ref>[https://www.sfchronicle.com/travel/article/California-Outdoors-Hall-of-Fame-inductees-13539700.php \"California Outdoors Hall of Fame inductees changed landscape\" by Tom Steinstra, Jan. 17, 2019.] Retrieved May 3, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\nTapon is the author of the ''WanderLearn Series'', which is a series of books about his adventures.<ref>Brotman, Barbara. (September 24, 2012) [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-09-24/news/ct-talk-brotman-geo-0924-20120924_1_finland-helsinki-map \"Getting to know the world around us\"] ''Chicago Tribune''. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref> He has written two books so far:\n\n*Tapon, Francis (2006), ''Hike Your Own Hike: 7 Life Lessons from Backpacking Across America'', 351 pages, {{ISBN|978-0-9765812-0-8}}.\n*Tapon, Francis (2012), ''The Hidden Europe: What Eastern Europeans Can Teach Us'', 736 pages, {{ISBN|978-0976581222}}.\n\nHe also wrote two chapters in ''Hikers' Stories From the Appalachian Trail'', edited by Kathryn Fulton, {{ISBN|978-0811712835}} (2012) Stackpole Books. The chapters are entitled \"The Final Stretch\" and \"A Thru-hiker's Motivation: Not Enlightenment, Just Ice Cream.\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://francistapon.com WanderLearn with Francis Tapon]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tapon, Francis}}\n[[Category:American travel writers]]\n[[Category:American self-help writers]]\n[[Category:Hikers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Amherst College alumni]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction outdoors writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American writer}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Francis Tapon\n| image        = Francis Tapon, head shot.jpg\n| caption      = Tapon in 2012\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1970|3|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| nationality  = American, French and Chilean\n|alma_mater = [[Amherst College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])<br />[[Harvard Business School]] ([[Masters of Business Administration|M.B.A.]])\n| occupation   = Author, nomad, public speaker, life coach\n| notableworks = ''Hike Your Own Hike''<br/>''The Hidden Europe''\n| website      = {{URL|http://FrancisTapon.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Francis Tapon''' (born March 10, 1970) is an [[author]], [[global nomad]], and [[public speaker]]. He has walked across the United States four times via its [[Triple Crown of Hiking|three major mountain ranges]]. He also walked across Spain twice. He was the first person to do a round-trip backpacking the [[Continental Divide Trail]]. In addition, he [[thru-hike]]d the [[Pacific Crest Trail]] and [[Appalachian Trail]] southbound. He has traveled to over 100 countries of the world.<ref>Krasny, Michael. (December 28, 2011). [http://www.kqed.org/a/forum/R201112291000 \"National radio interview\"]. KQED, San Francisco Public Radio, NPR affiliate. Retrieved November 1, 2013.</ref> Lastly, he is the author of the [[self-help]] travelogue ''Hike Your Own Hike'' and the [[travel narrative]] ''The Hidden Europe: What Eastern Europeans Can Teach Us''.<ref>NTD TV. [http://www.ntdtv.com/xtr/b5/2012/05/08/a697908.html.-%E8%88%8A%E9%87%91%E5%B1%B1%E4%BD%9C%E5%AE%B6%E9%81%8A%E6%9D%B1%E6%AD%90%E7%B1%B2%E6%94%BE%E6%A3%84%E5%85%B1%E7%94%A2%E6%94%BF%E6%AC%8A.html \"Chinese TV interview\"] Retrieved on November 2, 2013</ref> He traveled to all 54 [[African countries]] from 2013 to 2018 and climbed to the highest point of 50 of those countries.<ref>Frank Mallicoat [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_t8Q8pfLxqc \"KPIX CBS affiliate TV interview\"] Dec 18, 2012. Retrieved January 24, 2019.</ref><ref>Tom Stinstra [https://www.sfchronicle.com/sports/article/After-five-years-10-000-miles-in-Africa-Francis-13112246.php] July 29, 2018. Retrieved January 24, 2019.</ref> In 2019, he was inducted into the California Outdoors Hall of Fame.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Stienstra |first=Tom |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/outdoors/stienstra/article/California-Outdoors-Hall-of-Fame-inductees-13539700.php |title=California Outdoors Hall of Fame inductees changed landscape |date=January 17, 2019 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n==Early life and career==\nTapon's mother is from [[Chile]] and his father was from [[France]].<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/francis-tapon/ \"Huffington Post bio\"] Retrieved November 1, 2013</ref>\nTapon was born in [[San Francisco]],<ref>[http://www.goodreads.com/author/show/563037.Francis_Tapon/ \"Francis Tapon's biography\"]. Goodreads. Retrieved November 1, 2013.</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Apy1_Q0BI1w \"Interview on French American TV\"] skip to 0:50</ref> where he went to the [[French American International School (San Francisco)|French American International School]] until 10th grade, and then graduated from [[Lick-Wilmerding High School]].\n\nHe earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] [[cum laude]] in [[Religion]] from [[Amherst College]] in 1992.<ref>Lieber, Ben. [https://www.amherst.edu/alumni/learn/bookclub/pastfeatures/november2012] \"Amherst College Alumni Interview\" retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref> He worked in [[Latin America]] for [[Hitachi Data Systems]]. In 1997, he received his [[MBA]] from [[Harvard Business School]].<ref>Tapon, Francis (December 1, 2012) [https://www.alumni.hbs.edu/stories/Pages/story-bulletin.aspx?num=1188 \"The Billion Dollar Question\"]. ''Harvard Business School Bulletin''. Retrieved November 1, 2013.</ref>\n\nAfter [[Harvard]], he co-founded a [[Silicon Valley]] robotic vision company that was covered by [[The New York Times]].<ref>Lewis, Michael (March 1, 1998). [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0CEED8143EF932A35750C0A96E958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=print \"The Little Creepy Crawlers Who Will Eat You In The Night\"]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved November 1, 2013.</ref><ref>Stern, Rachel J. (April 23, 2012) [http://losgatos.patch.com/groups/arts-and-entertainment/p/the-hidden-europe-20-years-after-communism] \"'The Hidden Europe' Comes to Los Gatos\"] Patch.com. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref> Later, he consulted for [[Microsoft]] for 18 months. In 2006, he became a full-time travel writer.<ref>Stienstra, Tom. (February 24, 2008). [http://articles.sfgate.com/2008-02-24/sports/17140081_1_pacific-crest-trail-mexican-border-hike \"His life is a long, gratifying hike\"]. ''San Francisco Chronicle''. Retrieved November 1, 2013.</ref>\n\n==Travels==\n[[File:Francis-Tapon-photo1.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph|Tapon in [[Slovenia]], August 2010]]\nBelow is a chronology of Tapon's most notable travel experiences, which inspired his two books.\n\nIn 2001, he hiked the [[Appalachian Trail]].<ref>Lanza, Michael. (November 2008) [http://www.backpacker.com/november_2008_american_classic_hiking_the_appalachian_trail/destinations/12530?page=3 \"American Classic: Hiking the Appalachian Trail\"]. ''Backpacker Magazine''. Retrieved November 1, 2013.</ref> In 2004, he visited all the countries in [[Eastern Europe]].<ref>Tapon, Francis. (October 5, 2012) [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-2Bd8pNYH8A \"Francis Tapon's TEDx Talk\"]. TEDx Fillmore speech, San Francisco. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref> In 2006, he backpacked the [[Pacific Crest Trail]].<ref>Fulton, Kathryn. (2012) [https://books.google.com/books?id=2QJbyQZHYUYC&pg=PA159&lpg=PA159&dq=francis+tapon+pacific+crest+trail&source=bl&ots=PkTvd75X79&sig=MDiu3X2nl_BXb-2N_z4YAtbaPCQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5JVyUo2DGMqBhAffwYD4Ag&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=francis%20tapon%20pacific%20crest%20trail&f=false ''Hikers' Stories from the Appalachian Trail''], Stackpole Books, page 159. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 2007, he became the first person to walk from [[Mexico]] to [[Canada]] and back to Mexico along the [[Continental Divide Trail]].<ref>Tilin, Andrew. (June 2008) [http://www.backpacker.com/june_2008_feature_onion_mr_magoo_cdt/articles/12430?page=1 \"The Onion vs. Mr. Magoo \u2013 On your mark, get set ... hike. Inside a 5,600-mile footrace on the country's hardest trail.\"]. ''Backpacker Magazine''. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref><ref>M. Biggers, Ashley. (March 2008) \"There & Back Again\", ''New Mexico Magazine''</ref><ref>Bastone, Kelly (August 2008) \"Taking the High Way: Thru-hiking the Continental Divide Trail,\" ''5280'', pp. 70\u201373. Denver magazine reports on Francis Tapon's first-ever yo-yo of the CDT.</ref><ref>Wilt, Bernie. [http://www.practicalbackpacking.com/blog/archives/000035_pbp_episode_31_cdt_yoyo.php \"PBP Episode 31 \u2013 CDT Yo-Yo\"]. PracticalBackpacking.com. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref><ref>Reese, Janet. (19 June 2007). [http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2007/jun/19/5-questions-for-long-distance-hiker-francis/ \"5 questions for long-distance hiker Francis Tapon\"]. ''Rocky Mountain News''. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref>\nThis seven-month journey spanned over 5,600 miles.<ref>Stienstra, Tom. (March 9, 2008). [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/03/09/SPRRVE84U.DTL&hw=tapon&sn=002&sc=096 \"Good time to take inventory on gear \u2013 and yourself\"]. ''San Francisco Chronicle''. . Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref> Francis took the most circuitous, scenic, high, difficult route north and while returning south took the more expedient route on the way down.<ref>Manning, John. (April 8, 2008) [http://www.francistapon.com/images/press/TaponProfileTGO.pdf \"Francis Tapon: The first person to yo-yo America\u2019s wildest trail talks heating, eating and the philosophy of lightweight\"]. ''TGO Magazine''. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref> He hiked [[Ultralight backpacking|ultralight]] since his pack, without food and water, weighed under 6&nbsp;lbs (less than 3&nbsp;kg).<ref>Crooker, Carol. (September 12, 2007) [https://archive.is/20131105173923/http://www.backpackinglight.com/cgi-bin/backpackinglight/podcast_090407_francis_tapon_cdt_yo-yo.html \"Podcast: Francis Tapon is Set to Complete a Backpacking First \u2013 a CDT Yo-Yo\"]. Backpackinglight.com. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref><ref>Stienstra, Tom. (March 9, 2008) [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/03/09/SPRRVE84U.DTL&hw=tapon&sn=002&sc=096 \"Good time to take inventory on gear \u2013 and yourself\"]. ''San Francisco Chronicle''. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref>\n[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]] listed Francis Tapon's round trip on the Continental Divide Trail among one of the most notable feats of 2007.<ref>[http://www.nationalgeographic.com/adventure/best-of-adventure-2008/sports-trends.html \"Best of Adventure, Trends: New Leaf\"] ''National Geographic''. Retrieved November 2, 2012.</ref><ref>Lineback, Neal. (October 1, 2013)  [http://newswatch.nationalgeographic.com/2013/10/19/geography-in-the-news-americas-hiking-trails \"America's Hiking Trails\"] National Geographic: Geography in the News. Retrieved November 2, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2009, he walked across [[Spain]] twice: once by traversing the [[Pyrenees]] from the [[Mediterranean Sea]] to the [[Atlantic Ocean]], and then by hiking [[Way of St. James|El Camino de Santiago]].<ref>Bassets, Marc. (August 17, 2012) [http://francistapon.com/images/travels/spain/La-Vanguardia-17-08-2012.jpg \"El Disidente\"] ''La Vanguardia'' in Spanish. Retrieved November 2, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2008\u20132011, he visited over 40 European countries, including all the Eastern European ones.<ref>Delevett, Peter. (May 19, 2012) [http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/19/business/la-fi-social-travel-20120519/2 \"Social travel' start-ups help travelers gather friends\"] Page 2 of ''Los Angeles Times'' article. Retrieved November 2, 2013</ref><ref>Steves, Rick. (August 17, 2013) [http://www.ricksteves.com/radio/protected/descriptions.cfm?showID=463 \"Bumpy Balkans\"] National Radio Show. Retrieved November 2, 2013</ref><ref>Riddell, Joel. (August 2013)[http://www.newstalk910.com/player/?station=KKSF-AM&program_name=podcast&program_id=diningaround.xml&mid=22190615 \"Dining Around Interview\"] The interview starts at minute 17. NewsTalk 910, KKSF, San Francisco.</ref> He focused on finding Eastern European innovations.<ref>Tapon, Francis. (January 1, 2012) [http://francistapon.com/images/press/WashPost-Innovation.pdf \"Eastern Europe: Innovation's hidden hub\"] ''Washington Post'', page G4. Retrieved November 2. 2013.</ref><ref>Kolawole, Emi. (January 1, 2012) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/innovations/post/europe-the-credit-downgrade-and-what-it-means-for-innovation/2012/01/14/gIQASYJXyP_blog.html \"Europe, the credit downgrade and what it means for innovation\"] WashingtonPost.com. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Steves |first=Rick |url=http://www.ricksteves.com/radio/protected/descriptions.cfm?showID=411 |title=Program 297: Open Phones: Ask Rick; Francis Tapon Explores Eastern Europe |date=August 18, 2012 |access-date=November 1, 2013 |publisher=Rick Steves National Radio Show}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he summed up his travels to date and shared his lessons in his [[TEDx]] talk entitled, \"How and Why Travel Transforms You.\" It has over 100,000 views.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-2Bd8pNYH8A 18-min TEDx video] Retrieved June 3, 2017.</ref> \n\nIn March 2013, he entered Morocco and began a five-year trip to all 54 [[List of sovereign states and dependent territories in Africa|African]] countries. He never left the African continent. Half way through his trip, he met and married a Cameroonian, Rejoice Tapon, who traveled 31 of African countries with him.<ref>[https://francistapon.com/Travels/Africa/Engagement-Taking-the-Plunge How Francis Tapon proposed to Rejoice.] Retrieved April 22, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://francistapon.com/About/Birthday-Wedding-to-Celebrate-Francis-Rejoice-Marriage Francis and Rejoice Tapon marriage] Retrieved April 22, 2019.</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Tapon returned to a TEDx stage. He had just returned from 5.5 years of nonstop overland travel through all 54 African countries. Tapon shared a story about an African girl who was a \"black sheep\" in her society and what we can learn from it.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PVfADBIsgB8 18-min TEDx video \"Bring Out Your Inner Black Sheep\"] Retrieved May 3, 2019.</ref> \n\nHe returned to the United States in 2018. He plans to write his third book based on the experience. He filmed extensively and has raised over $24,000 to produce a [[Television pilot|pilot TV episode]] by November 2014.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Steves |first=Rick |url=http://www.ricksteves.com/radio/protected/descriptions.cfm?showID=435 |title=Program 314: Travel Portraits; Artist's Safari; Africa 54 |date=February 2, 2013 |access-date=November 1, 2013 |publisher=Rick Steves National Radio Show}}</ref><ref>[https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/ftapon/the-unseen-africa-tv-series-the-pilot-episode-moro Kickstarter Project: The Unseen Africa] Retrieved May 26, 2014</ref> [[Amazon.com]] and [[Lincoln Mercury]] selected him as the best example of someone who is fulfilling the dream of traveling the world.<ref>Amazon.com & Lincoln Mercury did a video profile of people who doing were doing 25 classic dreams [http://www.vimeo.com/718800 Video excerpt of the 'My Dream' campaign] Vimeo.com. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, he was inducted in the California Outdoors Hall of Fame, which includes [[John Muir]] and [[Ansel Adams]].<ref>[https://www.sfchronicle.com/travel/article/California-Outdoors-Hall-of-Fame-inductees-13539700.php \"California Outdoors Hall of Fame inductees changed landscape\" by Tom Steinstra, Jan. 17, 2019.] Retrieved May 3, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\nTapon is the author of the ''WanderLearn Series'', which is a series of books about his adventures.<ref>Brotman, Barbara. (September 24, 2012) [http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-09-24/news/ct-talk-brotman-geo-0924-20120924_1_finland-helsinki-map \"Getting to know the world around us\"] ''Chicago Tribune''. Retrieved November 2, 2013.</ref> He has written two books so far:\n\n*Tapon, Francis (2006), ''Hike Your Own Hike: 7 Life Lessons from Backpacking Across America'', 351 pages, {{ISBN|978-0-9765812-0-8}}.\n*Tapon, Francis (2012), ''The Hidden Europe: What Eastern Europeans Can Teach Us'', 736 pages, {{ISBN|978-0976581222}}.\n\nHe also wrote two chapters in ''Hikers' Stories From the Appalachian Trail'', edited by Kathryn Fulton, {{ISBN|978-0811712835}} (2012) Stackpole Books. The chapters are entitled \"The Final Stretch\" and \"A Thru-hiker's Motivation: Not Enlightenment, Just Ice Cream.\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://francistapon.com WanderLearn with Francis Tapon]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tapon, Francis}}\n[[Category:American travel writers]]\n[[Category:American self-help writers]]\n[[Category:Hikers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Amherst College alumni]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction outdoors writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Tapon"}
{"title_page": "Richard Caton (merchant)", "text_new": "{{Lead too short|date=February 2020}}\n{{infobox person\n|image=Richard Caton - Gilbert Stuart.jpg\n| birth_date    = 1763\n| birth_place   = [[Lancashire]], [[England]]\n| death_date    = {{dda|1845|05|19|1763}}\n| death_place   = [[Catonsville, Maryland]] \n| resting_place = [[Green Mount Cemetery]]\n| residence     = [[Castle Thunder (house)|Castle Thunder]]<br>[[Brooklandwood]]\n| occupation    = Merchant, real estate developer \n| parents       =\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Mary Carroll<br>|November 25, 1787|May 19, 1845|reason=his death}}\n| children      = [[Marianne Wellesley, Marchioness Wellesley]]<br>Elizabeth, Lady Stafford<br>Louisa, Duchess of Leeds<br>Emily MacTavish \n| relations     =\n}}\n'''Richard Caton''' (1763 \u2013 May 19, 1845) was an Englishman who became a [[Baltimore]] merchant.\n\n==Early life==\nCaton was born in 1763 in [[Lancashire]], [[England]].<ref name=\"colonial-settlers-md-va.\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.colonial-settlers-md-va.us/getperson.php?personID=I008004&tree=Tree1 |title=Richard Caton b. 1763 England d. 1845 Catonsville, Baltimore County, Maryland: Early Colonial Settlers of Southern Maryland and Virginia's Northern Neck Counties |website=www.colonial-settlers-md-va.us |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> He was a son of John Caton and the sister of Dorothy Caton, who married William Woodville, grandparents of artist [[Richard Caton Woodville]], himself the father of artist [[Richard Caton Woodville Jr.]]<ref name=\"Wolff\">{{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/richardcatonwood00wolf/page/208 |title=Richard Caton Woodville: American Painter, Artful Dodger |last=Wolff |first=Justin |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=2002 |isbn=978-0-691-07083-4 |location=Princeton |pages=[https://archive.org/details/richardcatonwood00wolf/page/208 208]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCaton left England and settled in Baltimore in 1785 as a merchant involved in the manufacture of cotton goods.<ref name=\"AccessGenealogy\">{{Cite news |url=https://accessgenealogy.com/maryland/caton-sisters-baltimore.htm |title=Caton Sisters of Baltimore |last=Dennis |work=Access Genealogy |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter his 1787 marriage, his father-in-law instructed him to develop area along the newly built [[Maryland Route 144#Ellicott City \u2013 Baltimore|Frederick Road]], which Carroll owned land next to, and which was used to transport tobacco south from plantations to the [[Patapsco River]] on horse-drawn wagons. He gave his name to the community and called it \"Catonville\", although the name was changed to \"Catonsville\" in the 1830s.<ref name=\"u-s-history\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.u-s-history.com/pages/h2789.html |title=History of Catonsville, Maryland |website=www.u-s-history.com |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1790, Caton built [[Brooklandwood]] in [[Baltimore County, Maryland|Baltimore County]], which was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1972.<ref>{{Cite web |url={{MHT url|id=70}} |title=Maryland Historical Trust |date=2008-10-05 |website=National Register of Historic Places: Brooklandwood |publisher=Maryland Historical Trust}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Castle Thunder marker.png|thumb|Marker at the present location of Castle Thunder on Frederick Road in Catonsville]]\nCaton was married to Mary \"Polly\" Carroll (1770\u20131846) at [[Annapolis]] on November 25, 1787. Polly was the daughter of [[Charles Carroll of Carrollton]], the last surviving signer of the [[Declaration of Independence]].<ref name=\"Luckett1937\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ngYNAAAAYAAJ |title=Maryland Women: Baltimore, Maryland, 1931-1942 |last=Luckett |first=Margie Hersh |date=1937 |publisher=King Bros., Incorporated Press |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>  After the wedding, Carroll gave Polly and Richard a home, known as [[Castle Thunder (house)|Castle Thunder]], which stood from 1787 to 1907.<ref name=\"Luckett1937\" /> Her younger sister Kitty Carroll married the lawyer and [[U.S. Senator]] [[Robert Goodloe Harper]].<ref name=\"Hanson2009\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u0AUCoIl4IcC&pg=PA141 |title=Old Kent: The Eastern Shore of Maryland |last=Hanson |first=George A. |date=2009 |publisher=Genealogical Publishing Com |isbn=9780806346328 |page=141 |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> They were the parents of four daughters who survived to maturity, including:<ref name=\"Maryland1829\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=twhRAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA182 |title=Laws of Maryland Made and Passed at a Session of Assembly |date=1829 |publisher=Frederick Green |page=182 |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Marianne Wellesley, Marchioness Wellesley|Marianne Caton]] (1788\u20131853), who married Robert Patterson, brother of [[Elizabeth Patterson Bonaparte|Elizabeth Patterson]] (wife of [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Bonaparte]]). After his death, she married the British statesman [[Richard Wellesley, 1st Marquess Wellesley]],<ref name=\"MarquessWellesley\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/wellesley1799.htm |title=Wellesley, Marquess (I, 1799 - 1842) |website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk |publisher=Heraldic Media Limited |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> brother of [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington]],<ref name=\"Larson2014\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DzAQBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT23 |title=Lincoln\u2019s Loyal Lady: Anna Ella Carroll, a Brief |last=Larson |first=C. Kay |date=2014 |publisher=Xlibris Corporation |isbn=9781499080353 |page=23 |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> who was believed to have been previously Marianne's [[Extramarital sex|paramour]].<ref name=\"Beirne1984\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WNso9EnqfxcC&pg=PA111 |title=The Amiable Baltimoreans |last=Francis F. Beirne |date=October 1984 |publisher=JHU Press |isbn=978-0-8018-2513-2 |pages=111\u2013}}</ref>\n*Elizabeth Caton (1790\u20131862), who married [[Baron Stafford|Sir George Strafford, 8th Baron Strafford]].<ref name=\"BaronStafford\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/staffordbaron1640.htm |title=Stafford, Baron (E, 1640) |website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk |publisher=Heraldic Media Limited |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Louisa Catharine Caton (1793\u20131874), who married [[Felton Hervey-Bathurst|Colonel Sir Felton Bathurst-Hervey, 1st Baronet]].<ref name=\"Hervey-Bathurst\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/herveybb1818.htm |title=Hervey-Bathurst (UK Baronet, 1818) |website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk |publisher=Heraldic Media Limited |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> After his death, she married [[Francis D'Arcy-Osborne, 7th Duke of Leeds|Francis D'Arcy-Osborne]], later the [[Duke of Leeds|7th Duke of Leeds]].<ref name=\"DukeLeeds\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/leeds1694.htm |title=Leeds, Duke of (E, 1694 - 1964) |website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk |publisher=Heraldic Media Limited |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Emily Caton (1794/5\u20131867), who married the Scottish born [[John MacTavish (British Consul)|John McTavish]], British Consul at Baltimore. They lived at [[Carrollton Hall]], near [[Doughoregan Manor]].<ref name=\"Wise2006\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6sTc6UuiYS0C&pg=PT79 |title=Ellicott City |last=Wise |first=Marsha Wight |date=2006 |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |isbn=9781439617281 |page=79 |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis eldest three girls were known as \"The Three American Graces\" due to their beauty and the fact that all married into the [[English aristocracy]].  His youngest daughter remained in Maryland and ran the family finances.  Caton died in [[Catonsville, Maryland]] on May 19, 1845 in Baltimore and was buried at [[Green Mount Cemetery]]. At his death, he died insolvent, leaving $2,762.<ref name=\"Wake2012\" />  His widow died the following year on November 14, 1846, leaving a personal fortune of \u00a3186,000 (roughly equivalent to $19.9 million).<ref name=\"Wake2012\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9vIQ4J28Tn8C&pg=PA3 |title=Sisters of Fortune: America's Caton Sisters at Home and Abroad |last=Wake |first=Jehanne |date=2012 |publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]] |isbn=9781451607635 |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Descendants===\nThrough his youngest daughter Emily, his only child to have children, he was a grandfather of four, including [[Charles Carroll MacTavish]] (1818\u20131868),<ref name=\"1887Convent\">{{Cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1887/03/06/100897814.pdf |title=Entered a Holy Life; a Baltimore Belle Takes the White Veil in Belgium. |date=6 March 1887 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> who married Marcella Scott (a daughter of Gen. [[Winfield Scott]]);<ref name=\"Caldwell1994\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dYdWBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA534 |title=American Paintings in The Metropolitan Museum of Art. Vol. 1: A Catalogue of Works by Artists Born by 1815 |last=Caldwell |first=John |last2=Roque |first2=Oswaldo Rodriguez |last3=Johnson |first3=Dale T. |date=1994 |publisher=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] |page=534 |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> Mary Wellesley MacTavish (1826\u20131850), who married Hon. Henry George Howard (youngest son of [[George Howard, 6th Earl of Carlisle]]); Alexander Simon MacTavish (1829\u20131863), who married Ellen Gilmor; and Richard Caton MacTavish (1831\u20131841), who died young.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Sisters of Fortune |last=Wake |first=Jehanne |publisher=A Touchstone Book published by Simom & Schuster |year=2010}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n* [[Catonsville, Maryland]] was named in his honor.<ref name=\"Wake2012\" />\n* [[Caton, New York]] (in [[Steuben County, New York]] near the [[Genesee River]]) was named in his honor.<ref name=\"Wake2012\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{fg|80714860}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caton, Richard}}\n[[Category:1763 births]]\n[[Category:1845 deaths]]\n[[Category:Carroll family]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American merchants]]\n[[Category:Burials in Maryland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Lead too short|date=February 2020}}\n{{infobox person\n|image=Richard Caton - Gilbert Stuart.jpg\n| birth_date    = 1763\n| birth_place   = [[Lancashire]], [[England]]\n| death_date    = {{dda|1845|05|19|1763}}\n| death_place   = [[Catonsville, Maryland]] \n| resting_place = [[Green Mount Cemetery]]\n| residence     = [[Castle Thunder (house)|Castle Thunder]]<br>[[Brooklandwood]]\n| occupation    = Merchant, real estate developer \n| parents       =\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Mary Carroll<br>|November 25, 1787|May 19, 1845|reason=his death}}\n| children      = [[Marianne Wellesley, Marchioness Wellesley]]<br>Elizabeth, Lady Stafford<br>Louisa, Duchess of Leeds<br>Emily MacTavish \n| relations     =\n}}\n'''Richard Caton''' (1763 \u2013 May 19, 1845) was an Englishman who became a [[Baltimore]] merchant.\n\n==Early life==\nCaton was born in 1763 in [[Lancashire]], [[England]].<ref name=\"colonial-settlers-md-va.\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.colonial-settlers-md-va.us/getperson.php?personID=I008004&tree=Tree1 |title=Richard Caton b. 1763 England d. 1845 Catonsville, Baltimore County, Maryland: Early Colonial Settlers of Southern Maryland and Virginia's Northern Neck Counties |website=www.colonial-settlers-md-va.us |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> He was a son of John Caton and the sister of Dorothy Caton, who married William Woodville, grandparents of artist [[Richard Caton Woodville]], himself the father of artist [[Richard Caton Woodville Jr.]]<ref name=\"Wolff\">{{Cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/richardcatonwood00wolf/page/208 |title=Richard Caton Woodville: American Painter, Artful Dodger |last=Wolff |first=Justin |publisher=Princeton University Press |year=2002 |isbn=978-0-691-07083-4 |location=Princeton |pages=[https://archive.org/details/richardcatonwood00wolf/page/208 208]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCaton left England and settled in Baltimore in 1785 as a merchant involved in the manufacture of cotton goods.<ref name=\"AccessGenealogy\">{{Cite news |url=https://accessgenealogy.com/maryland/caton-sisters-baltimore.htm |title=Caton Sisters of Baltimore |last=Dennis |work=Access Genealogy |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter his 1787 marriage, his father-in-law instructed him to develop area along the newly built [[Maryland Route 144#Ellicott City \u2013 Baltimore|Frederick Road]], which Carroll owned land next to, and which was used to transport tobacco south from plantations to the [[Patapsco River]] on horse-drawn wagons. He gave his name to the community and called it \"Catonville\", although the name was changed to \"Catonsville\" in the 1830s.<ref name=\"u-s-history\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.u-s-history.com/pages/h2789.html |title=History of Catonsville, Maryland |website=www.u-s-history.com |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1790, Caton built [[Brooklandwood]] in [[Baltimore County, Maryland|Baltimore County]], which was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1972.<ref>{{Cite web |url={{MHT url|id=70}} |title=Maryland Historical Trust |date=2008-10-05 |website=National Register of Historic Places: Brooklandwood |publisher=Maryland Historical Trust}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Castle Thunder marker.png|thumb|Marker at the present location of Castle Thunder on Frederick Road in Catonsville]]\nCaton was married to Mary \"Polly\" Carroll (1770\u20131846) at [[Annapolis]] on November 25, 1787. Polly was the daughter of [[Charles Carroll of Carrollton]], the last surviving signer of the [[Declaration of Independence]].<ref name=\"Luckett1937\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ngYNAAAAYAAJ |title=Maryland Women: Baltimore, Maryland, 1931-1942 |last=Luckett |first=Margie Hersh |date=1937 |publisher=King Bros., Incorporated Press |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>  After the wedding, Carroll gave Polly and Richard a home, known as [[Castle Thunder (house)|Castle Thunder]], which stood from 1787 to 1907.<ref name=\"Luckett1937\" /> Her younger sister Kitty Carroll married the lawyer and [[U.S. Senator]] [[Robert Goodloe Harper]].<ref name=\"Hanson2009\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u0AUCoIl4IcC&pg=PA141 |title=Old Kent: The Eastern Shore of Maryland |last=Hanson |first=George A. |date=2009 |publisher=Genealogical Publishing Com |isbn=9780806346328 |page=141 |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> They were the parents of four daughters who survived to maturity, including:<ref name=\"Maryland1829\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=twhRAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA182 |title=Laws of Maryland Made and Passed at a Session of Assembly |date=1829 |publisher=Frederick Green |page=182 |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[[Marianne Wellesley, Marchioness Wellesley|Marianne Caton]] (1788\u20131853), who married Robert Patterson, brother of [[Elizabeth Patterson Bonaparte|Elizabeth Patterson]] (wife of [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Bonaparte]]). After his death, she married the British statesman [[Richard Wellesley, 1st Marquess Wellesley]],<ref name=\"MarquessWellesley\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/wellesley1799.htm |title=Wellesley, Marquess (I, 1799 - 1842) |website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk |publisher=Heraldic Media Limited |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> brother of [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington]],<ref name=\"Larson2014\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DzAQBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT23 |title=Lincoln\u2019s Loyal Lady: Anna Ella Carroll, a Brief |last=Larson |first=C. Kay |date=2014 |publisher=Xlibris Corporation |isbn=9781499080353 |page=23 |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> who was believed to have been previously Marianne's [[Extramarital sex|paramour]].<ref name=\"Beirne1984\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WNso9EnqfxcC&pg=PA111 |title=The Amiable Baltimoreans |last=Francis F. Beirne |date=October 1984 |publisher=JHU Press |isbn=978-0-8018-2513-2 |pages=111\u2013}}</ref>\n*Elizabeth Caton (1790\u20131862), who married [[Baron Stafford|Sir George Strafford, 8th Baron Strafford]].<ref name=\"BaronStafford\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/staffordbaron1640.htm |title=Stafford, Baron (E, 1640) |website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk |publisher=Heraldic Media Limited |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Louisa Catharine Caton (1793\u20131874), who married [[Felton Hervey-Bathurst|Colonel Sir Felton Bathurst-Hervey, 1st Baronet]].<ref name=\"Hervey-Bathurst\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/herveybb1818.htm |title=Hervey-Bathurst (UK Baronet, 1818) |website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk |publisher=Heraldic Media Limited |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> After his death, she married [[Francis D'Arcy-Osborne, 7th Duke of Leeds|Francis D'Arcy-Osborne]], later the [[Duke of Leeds|7th Duke of Leeds]].<ref name=\"DukeLeeds\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/leeds1694.htm |title=Leeds, Duke of (E, 1694 - 1964) |website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk |publisher=Heraldic Media Limited |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Emily Caton (1794/5-1867), who married the Scottish born [[John MacTavish (British Consul)|John McTavish]], British Consul at Baltimore. They lived at [[Carrollton Hall]], near [[Doughoregan Manor]].<ref name=\"Wise2006\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6sTc6UuiYS0C&pg=PT79 |title=Ellicott City |last=Wise |first=Marsha Wight |date=2006 |publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]] |isbn=9781439617281 |page=79 |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis eldest three girls were known as \"The Three American Graces\" due to their beauty and the fact that all married into the [[English aristocracy]].  His youngest daughter remained in Maryland and ran the family finances.  Caton died in [[Catonsville, Maryland]] on May 19, 1845 in Baltimore and was buried at [[Green Mount Cemetery]]. At his death, he died insolvent, leaving $2,762.<ref name=\"Wake2012\" />  His widow died the following year on November 14, 1846, leaving a personal fortune of \u00a3186,000 (roughly equivalent to $19.9 million).<ref name=\"Wake2012\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9vIQ4J28Tn8C&pg=PA3 |title=Sisters of Fortune: America's Caton Sisters at Home and Abroad |last=Wake |first=Jehanne |date=2012 |publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]] |isbn=9781451607635 |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Descendants===\nThrough his youngest daughter Emily, his only child to have children, he was a grandfather of four, including [[Charles Carroll MacTavish]] (1818\u20131868),<ref name=\"1887Convent\">{{Cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1887/03/06/100897814.pdf |title=Entered a Holy Life; a Baltimore Belle Takes the White Veil in Belgium. |date=6 March 1887 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> who married Marcella Scott (a daughter of Gen. [[Winfield Scott]]);<ref name=\"Caldwell1994\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dYdWBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA534 |title=American Paintings in The Metropolitan Museum of Art. Vol. 1: A Catalogue of Works by Artists Born by 1815 |last=Caldwell |first=John |last2=Roque |first2=Oswaldo Rodriguez |last3=Johnson |first3=Dale T. |date=1994 |publisher=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] |page=534 |language=en |access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref> Mary Wellesley MacTavish (1826\u20131850), who married Hon. Henry George Howard (youngest son of [[George Howard, 6th Earl of Carlisle]]); Alexander Simon MacTavish (1829\u20131863), who married Ellen Gilmor; and Richard Caton MacTavish (1831\u20131841), who died young.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Sisters of Fortune |last=Wake |first=Jehanne |publisher=A Touchstone Book published by Simom & Schuster |year=2010}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n* [[Catonsville, Maryland]] was named in his honor.<ref name=\"Wake2012\" />\n* [[Caton, New York]] (in [[Steuben County, New York]] near the [[Genesee River]]) was named in his honor.<ref name=\"Wake2012\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{fg|80714860}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caton, Richard}}\n[[Category:1763 births]]\n[[Category:1845 deaths]]\n[[Category:Carroll family]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American merchants]]\n[[Category:Burials in Maryland]]\n", "name_user": "Melofors", "label": "safe", "comment": "hyphen \u2192 en dash perWP:RANGE", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Caton_(merchant)"}
{"title_page": "Lia Finocchiaro", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name        = Lia Finocchiaro\n|honorific-suffix = [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n|image       = [[File:Lia-finnochiaro-wide170px (1).png|Lia-finnochiaro-wide170px (1)]]\n|alt         = \n|caption     = \n|office = Leader of the [[Country Liberal Party]]\n|term_start = 1 February 2020\n|term_end = \n|predecessor = [[Gary Higgins]]\n|deputy = [[Gary Higgins]]\n|successor = \n|office1 = [[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n|term_start1 = 1 February 2020\n|term_end1 = \n|deputy1 = [[Gary Higgins]]\n|predecessor1 = [[Gary Higgins]]\n|successor1 = \n|office2 = Deputy [[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n|term_start2 = 2 September 2016\n|term_end2 = 1 February 2020\n|predecessor2 = [[Lynne Walker (politician)|Lynne Walker]]\n|successor2 = [[Gary Higgins]]\n|office3 = Deputy Leader of the [[Country Liberal Party]]\n|term_start3 = 2 September 2016\n|term_end3 = 1 February 2020\n|predecessor3 = [[Peter Styles (politician)|Peter Styles]]\n|successor3 = [[Gary Higgins]]\n|constituency_AM4 = [[Electoral division of Spillett|Spillett]]\n|assembly4    = Northern Territory Legislative\n|majority4    = \n|term_start4  = 27 August 2016\n|term_end4    = \n|predecessor4 = ''new seat''\n|successor4   = \n|constituency_AM5 = [[Electoral division of Drysdale|Drysdale]]\n|assembly5    = Northern Territory Legislative\n|majority5    = \n|term_start5  = 25 August 2012\n|term_end5    = 27 August 2016\n|predecessor5 = [[Ross Bohlin]]\n|successor5   = [[Eva Lawler]]\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1984|9|20|df=yes}}\n|birth_place        = [[Darwin, Northern Territory]], Australia\n|birthname          = Lia Emele Finocchiaro\n|nationality        = Australian\n|party              = [[Country Liberal Party]]\n|spouse             = Sam Burke\n|relations = [[Denis Burke (Australian politician)|Denis Burke]] (father-in-law)\n|residence          = [[Palmerston, Northern Territory]]\n|alma_mater         = [[University of Adelaide]]\n|profession         = Lawyer\n}}\n'''Lia Emele Finocchiaro''' (born 20 September 1984) is an Australian politician. She has been a [[Country Liberal Party]] member of the [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]] for the seat of [[Electoral division of Spillett|Spillett]] since her [[2016 Northern Territory general election|election in 2016]]. She became [[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|Leader of the Opposition]] in the Northern Territory after the resignation of [[Gary Higgins]] on 1 February 2020.  \nShe was previously the member for [[Electoral division of Drysdale|Drysdale]] from [[2012 Northern Territory general election|2012]] to 2016.\n\n==Early life==\nFinocchiaro was born in the Northern Territory and grew up in [[Palmerston, Northern Territory|Palmerston]]. She attended local primary schools before completing her secondary education at [[Kormilda College]].<ref name=stories>{{cite news|url=https://www.territorystories.nt.gov.au/jspui/handle/10070/243184|title=Lia Finocchiaro|publisher=Territory Stories|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref> While in high school, she became \"the highest-ranking army cadet in the Northern Territory\".<ref name=ABCprofile>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-08-29/lia-finocchiaro-may-be-only-opposition-mla-in-nt-after-election/7795014|title=Who is Lia Finocchiaro, who may be the only opposition MLA in NT Parliament?|last=La Canna|first=Xavier|publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=2016-08-29}}</ref> She studied the [[International Baccalaureate]] diploma, then graduated with a double degree in law and international studies from the [[University of Adelaide]].<ref name=aoty>[http://www.australianoftheyear.org.au/recipients/?m=lia-finocchiaro-2012 NT Young Australian of the Year 2012 - Territory Finalist] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316213102/http://www.australianoftheyear.org.au/recipients/?m=lia-finocchiaro-2012 |date=16 March 2012 }}, Australian of the Year, 2012.</ref> She returned to Darwin in 2008, and was admitted as a legal practitioner in the Northern Territory, commencing work as a graduate clerk at the [[Clayton Utz]] law firm. She also received a Graduate Diploma of Legal Practice from [[Charles Darwin University]].<ref name=ntvotes>[http://www.abc.net.au/elections/nt/2012/guide/drys.htm Drysdale (Key Seat)], ''Northern Territory Votes 2012'', Australian Broadcasting Corporation, August 2012.</ref>\n\n==Parliament==\nIn 2012, the [[Country Liberal Party]] preselected Finocchiaro for the central Palmerston seat of [[Electoral division of Drysdale|Drysdale]] in that year's election, instead of sitting CLP member [[Ross Bohlin]], who unsuccessfully ran against her as a conservative independent.<ref name=ntnews>Crawford, Sarah: [http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2012/04/23/300221_ntnews.html New face of Drysdale], ''NT News'', 23 April 2012.</ref> She was the youngest MLA in the history of the Legislative Assembly.<ref name=ABCprofile/>\n\nOn 7 March 2013, Finocchiaro was elevated to the [[Second Mills Ministry]], becoming Minister for Sport and Recreation, Racing, Statehood, Young Territorians and Senior Territorians.  Aged 28, she was the youngest minister in Territory history.<ref name=ministry>{{cite news|last=La Canna|first=Xavier|title=Infighting, insults plague NT government|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/giles-went-after-nt-top-job-anderson-says/story-fn3dxiwe-1226592677580|accessdate=12 March 2013|newspaper=The Australian|date=7 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cabinet Reshuffle|url=http://newsroom.nt.gov.au/index.cfm?fuseaction=viewRelease&id=10461&d=5|work=Media release|publisher=Terry Mills MLA|accessdate=14 March 2013|date=7 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412225533/http://newsroom.nt.gov.au/index.cfm?fuseaction=viewRelease&id=10461&d=5|archivedate=12 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=ABCprofile/> However, she was dropped from the ministry on 14 March after [[Adam Giles]] successfully challenged then-Chief Minister [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]] only a week later.<ref>{{cite news|title=Angry Mills says turns his back on Giles cabinet|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-03-14/mills-arrives-back-spurns-cabinet/4573472|accessdate=14 March 2013|newspaper=ABC News|date=14 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a redistribution of electoral boundaries, Finocchiaro sought CLP preselection for the new seat of [[Electoral division of Spillett|Spillett]], taking in strong conservative suburbs between Darwin and Palmerston\u2014including her base in [[Durack, Northern Territory|Durack]].  She defeated Treasurer [[Dave Tollner]] for CLP preselection.  Finocchiaro went into the [[2016 Northern Territory general election|2016 election]] with a notional majority of 17.9%, making Spillett the CLP's safest seat in Darwin/Palmerston at the time.\n\n==CLP deputy leadership==\nOn election night, the Territory swung heavily to [[Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)|Labor]], which won a landslide majority government.  However, Finocchiaro weathered this massive Labor wave with only a small swing against her in Spillett, proving to be in the least danger of the CLP's elected members. She was the only CLP member whose reelection was assured on election night, and for a few days it was possible that she would be the only CLP member left in the legislature.<ref name=ABCprofile/> Ultimately, Finocchiaro was joined by fellow second-term member [[Gary Higgins]].  Meanwhile, her previous seat of Drysdale was lost to Labor candidate [[Eva Lawler]].\n\nOn 2 September, Higgins, the sole survivor of the Giles cabinet, became CLP leader and [[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|opposition leader]], with Finocchiaro as his deputy.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-09-02/gary-higgins-becomes-country-liberals-new-leader-in-nt/7810772 | title=Gary Higgins becomes Country Liberals' new leader, Lia Finnochiaro his deputy | work=Australian Broadcasting Corporation | date=2 September 2016 | accessdate=2 September 2016}}</ref> Finnochiaro faced the task of helping the CLP recover from one of the worst defeats of a sitting government at the state or territory level in Australia. The CLP was recognised as the Official Opposition after the Solicitor-General advised that the five independents could not realistically form an alternative government. Although the CLP was well short of the numbers for official status in the chamber, the new Labor government of [[Michael Gunner]] promised that the CLP would be properly resourced as an opposition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-08-30/independents-wil-not-be-recognised-at-opposition-in-nt/7799786|title=Independents won't be recognised as opposition in NT: official advice|last=Oaten|first=James|publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=2016-08-30}}</ref>\n\nAs the sole opposition MPs in the Assembly, Higgins and Finocchiaro divided all opposition portfolios between them. Finocchiaro served as Shadow Minister for Justice and Attorney-General, as well as Shadow Minister for Police, Fire and Emergency Services, Health, Children, Territory Families, Education, Trade, and Essential Services.<ref>[https://parliament.nt.gov.au/members-of-parliament/shadow-ministry Shadow Ministry] for 13th Legislative Assembly</ref> She also serves as Opposition Whip.<ref>https://www.garyhiggins.com.au/team</ref> Under these circumstances it was unusual that Finocchiaro is given this position, since the Opposition Whip is responsible for ensuring party MPs toe the official party line. However, Finocchiaro did not have any responsibility to keep anyone in line since there were only two members in the CLP party room, herself and Higgins.\n\n==Leader of the Opposition==\nOn 1 February 2020, Higgins resigned as CLP leader and opposition leader, with Finocchiaro replacing him.<ref name=\"oppleader\">{{cite news |last1=Vivian |first1=Steve |title=Country Liberal Party ''100 per cent\" behind new leader Lia Finocchiaro |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-20/gary-higgins-resigns-as-clp-leader-ahead-of-2020-nt-election/11882108 |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=ABC News |date=20 January 2020 |language=en-AU}}</ref> Former [[Chief Minister of the Northern Territory|Chief Minister]] and Territory Alliance Leader [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]] claimed to have replaced her as Opposition Leader on 18 March 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.ntnews.com.au/news/northern-territory/robyn-lambley-joins-terry-mills-territory-alliance-sets-up-almighty-clp-showdown/news-story/b1a09c5f1a7595e96d222b9357b1435e|title = Territory Alliance says it has taken NT Opposition status|accessdate = 24 Mar 2020}}</ref> however this claim was not formalised by the Legislative Assembly.\n\nOn 24 March, Finocchiaro raised a motion under standing orders which allowed the assembly to decide on the opposition party, with the CLP winning opposition status by 5 votes to 3.<ref name=\"oppreturn\">{{cite news |last1=Aikman |first1=Amos |title=NT parliament again resolves that opposition should change |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/nt-parliament-again-resolves-that-opposition-should-change/news-story/2823fe70c6fe243189d84425474e5708 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The Australian |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFinocchiaro is married to Sam Burke, the son of former NT chief minister [[Denis Burke (Australian politician)|Denis Burke]]. She is of Italian descent and has been \"heavily involved in the NT's Italian community\",<ref name=ABCprofile/> including as CEO of the Italian Festival Association of the Northern Territory.<ref name=stories/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.countryliberals.org.au/members.php?id=42 Lia Finocchiaro \u2013 Candidate for Drysdale (Country Liberal Party)]\n*{{Twitter}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-nt}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ross Bohlin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral division of Drysdale|Drysdale]]|years=2012\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Eva Lawler]]}}\n{{s-new|seat}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral division of Spillett|Spillett]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gary Higgins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2020}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lynne Walker (politician)|Lynne Walker]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= Deputy [[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2016\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gary Higgins]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gary Higgins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Country Liberal Party]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Styles (politician)|Peter Styles]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= Deputy Leader of the [[Country Liberal Party]]|years=2016\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gary Higgins]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NTCurrentMPs}}\n{{Leaders of the Country Liberal Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finocchiaro, Lia}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Country Liberal Party members of the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition in the Northern Territory]]\n[[Category:Australian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Adelaide Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Charles Darwin University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name        = Lia Finocchiaro\n|honorific-suffix = [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n|image       = [[File:Lia-finnochiaro-wide170px (1).png|Lia-finnochiaro-wide170px (1)]]\n|alt         = \n|caption     = \n|office = Leader of the [[Country Liberal Party]]\n|term_start = 1 February 2020\n|term_end = \n|predecessor = [[Gary Higgins]]\n|deputy = [[Gary Higgins]]\n|successor = \n|office1 = [[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n|term_start1 = 1 February 2020\n|term_end1 = \n|deputy1 = [[Gary Higgins]]\n|predecessor1 = [[Gary Higgins]]\n|successor1 = \n|office2 = Deputy [[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n|term_start2 = 2 September 2016\n|term_end2 = 1 February 2020\n|predecessor2 = [[Lynne Walker (politician)|Lynne Walker]]\n|successor2 = [[Gary Higgins]]\n|office3 = Deputy Leader of the [[Country Liberal Party]]\n|term_start3 = 2 September 2016\n|term_end3 = 1 February 2020\n|predecessor3 = [[Peter Styles]]\n|successor3 = [[Gary Higgins]]\n|constituency_AM4 = [[Electoral division of Spillett|Spillett]]\n|assembly4    = Northern Territory Legislative\n|majority4    = \n|term_start4  = 27 August 2016\n|term_end4    = \n|predecessor4 = ''new seat''\n|successor4   = \n|constituency_AM5 = [[Electoral division of Drysdale|Drysdale]]\n|assembly5    = Northern Territory Legislative\n|majority5    = \n|term_start5  = 25 August 2012\n|term_end5    = 27 August 2016\n|predecessor5 = [[Ross Bohlin]]\n|successor5   = [[Eva Lawler]]\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1984|9|20|df=yes}}\n|birth_place        = [[Darwin, Northern Territory]], Australia\n|birthname          = Lia Emele Finocchiaro\n|nationality        = Australian\n|party              = [[Country Liberal Party]]\n|spouse             = Sam Burke\n|relations = [[Denis Burke (Australian politician)|Denis Burke]] (father-in-law)\n|residence          = [[Palmerston, Northern Territory]]\n|alma_mater         = [[University of Adelaide]]\n|profession         = Lawyer\n}}\n'''Lia Emele Finocchiaro''' (born 20 September 1984) is an Australian politician. She has been a [[Country Liberal Party]] member of the [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]] for the seat of [[Electoral division of Spillett|Spillett]] since her [[2016 Northern Territory general election|election in 2016]]. She became [[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|Leader of the Opposition]] in the Northern Territory after the resignation of [[Gary Higgins]] on 1 February 2020.  \nShe was previously the member for [[Electoral division of Drysdale|Drysdale]] from [[2012 Northern Territory general election|2012]] to 2016.\n\n==Early life==\nFinocchiaro was born in the Northern Territory and grew up in [[Palmerston, Northern Territory|Palmerston]]. She attended local primary schools before completing her secondary education at [[Kormilda College]].<ref name=stories>{{cite news|url=https://www.territorystories.nt.gov.au/jspui/handle/10070/243184|title=Lia Finocchiaro|publisher=Territory Stories|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref> While in high school, she became \"the highest-ranking army cadet in the Northern Territory\".<ref name=ABCprofile>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-08-29/lia-finocchiaro-may-be-only-opposition-mla-in-nt-after-election/7795014|title=Who is Lia Finocchiaro, who may be the only opposition MLA in NT Parliament?|last=La Canna|first=Xavier|publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=2016-08-29}}</ref> She studied the [[International Baccalaureate]] diploma, then graduated with a double degree in law and international studies from the [[University of Adelaide]].<ref name=aoty>[http://www.australianoftheyear.org.au/recipients/?m=lia-finocchiaro-2012 NT Young Australian of the Year 2012 - Territory Finalist] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316213102/http://www.australianoftheyear.org.au/recipients/?m=lia-finocchiaro-2012 |date=16 March 2012 }}, Australian of the Year, 2012.</ref> She returned to Darwin in 2008, and was admitted as a legal practitioner in the Northern Territory, commencing work as a graduate clerk at the [[Clayton Utz]] law firm. She also received a Graduate Diploma of Legal Practice from [[Charles Darwin University]].<ref name=ntvotes>[http://www.abc.net.au/elections/nt/2012/guide/drys.htm Drysdale (Key Seat)], ''Northern Territory Votes 2012'', Australian Broadcasting Corporation, August 2012.</ref>\n\n==Parliament==\nIn 2012, the [[Country Liberal Party]] preselected Finocchiaro for the central Palmerston seat of [[Electoral division of Drysdale|Drysdale]] in that year's election, instead of sitting CLP member [[Ross Bohlin]], who unsuccessfully ran against her as a conservative independent.<ref name=ntnews>Crawford, Sarah: [http://www.ntnews.com.au/article/2012/04/23/300221_ntnews.html New face of Drysdale], ''NT News'', 23 April 2012.</ref> She was the youngest MLA in the history of the Legislative Assembly.<ref name=ABCprofile/>\n\nOn 7 March 2013, Finocchiaro was elevated to the [[Second Mills Ministry]], becoming Minister for Sport and Recreation, Racing, Statehood, Young Territorians and Senior Territorians.  Aged 28, she was the youngest minister in Territory history.<ref name=ministry>{{cite news|last=La Canna|first=Xavier|title=Infighting, insults plague NT government|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/giles-went-after-nt-top-job-anderson-says/story-fn3dxiwe-1226592677580|accessdate=12 March 2013|newspaper=The Australian|date=7 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cabinet Reshuffle|url=http://newsroom.nt.gov.au/index.cfm?fuseaction=viewRelease&id=10461&d=5|work=Media release|publisher=Terry Mills MLA|accessdate=14 March 2013|date=7 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412225533/http://newsroom.nt.gov.au/index.cfm?fuseaction=viewRelease&id=10461&d=5|archivedate=12 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=ABCprofile/> However, she was dropped from the ministry on 14 March after [[Adam Giles]] successfully challenged then-Chief Minister [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]] only a week later.<ref>{{cite news|title=Angry Mills says turns his back on Giles cabinet|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-03-14/mills-arrives-back-spurns-cabinet/4573472|accessdate=14 March 2013|newspaper=ABC News|date=14 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a redistribution of electoral boundaries, Finocchiaro sought CLP preselection for the new seat of [[Electoral division of Spillett|Spillett]], taking in strong conservative suburbs between Darwin and Palmerston\u2014including her base in [[Durack, Northern Territory|Durack]].  She defeated Treasurer [[Dave Tollner]] for CLP preselection.  Finocchiaro went into the [[2016 Northern Territory general election|2016 election]] with a notional majority of 17.9%, making Spillett the CLP's safest seat in Darwin/Palmerston at the time.\n\n==CLP deputy leadership==\nOn election night, the Territory swung heavily to [[Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)|Labor]], which won a landslide majority government.  However, Finocchiaro weathered this massive Labor wave with only a small swing against her in Spillett, proving to be in the least danger of the CLP's elected members. She was the only CLP member whose reelection was assured on election night, and for a few days it was possible that she would be the only CLP member left in the legislature.<ref name=ABCprofile/> Ultimately, Finocchiaro was joined by fellow second-term member [[Gary Higgins]].  Meanwhile, her previous seat of Drysdale was lost to Labor candidate [[Eva Lawler]].\n\nOn 2 September, Higgins, the sole survivor of the Giles cabinet, became CLP leader and [[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|opposition leader]], with Finocchiaro as his deputy.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-09-02/gary-higgins-becomes-country-liberals-new-leader-in-nt/7810772 | title=Gary Higgins becomes Country Liberals' new leader, Lia Finnochiaro his deputy | work=Australian Broadcasting Corporation | date=2 September 2016 | accessdate=2 September 2016}}</ref> Finnochiaro faced the task of helping the CLP recover from one of the worst defeats of a sitting government at the state or territory level in Australia. The CLP was recognised as the Official Opposition after the Solicitor-General advised that the five independents could not realistically form an alternative government. Although the CLP was well short of the numbers for official status in the chamber, the new Labor government of [[Michael Gunner]] promised that the CLP would be properly resourced as an opposition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-08-30/independents-wil-not-be-recognised-at-opposition-in-nt/7799786|title=Independents won't be recognised as opposition in NT: official advice|last=Oaten|first=James|publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=2016-08-30}}</ref>\n\nAs the sole opposition MPs in the Assembly, Higgins and Finocchiaro divided all opposition portfolios between them. Finocchiaro served as Shadow Minister for Justice and Attorney-General, as well as Shadow Minister for Police, Fire and Emergency Services, Health, Children, Territory Families, Education, Trade, and Essential Services.<ref>[https://parliament.nt.gov.au/members-of-parliament/shadow-ministry Shadow Ministry] for 13th Legislative Assembly</ref> She also serves as Opposition Whip.<ref>https://www.garyhiggins.com.au/team</ref> Under these circumstances it was unusual that Finocchiaro is given this position, since the Opposition Whip is responsible for ensuring party MPs toe the official party line. However, Finocchiaro did not have any responsibility to keep anyone in line since there were only two members in the CLP party room, herself and Higgins.\n\n==Leader of the Opposition==\nOn 1 February 2020, Higgins resigned as CLP leader and opposition leader, with Finocchiaro replacing him.<ref name=\"oppleader\">{{cite news |last1=Vivian |first1=Steve |title=Country Liberal Party ''100 per cent\" behind new leader Lia Finocchiaro |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-20/gary-higgins-resigns-as-clp-leader-ahead-of-2020-nt-election/11882108 |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=ABC News |date=20 January 2020 |language=en-AU}}</ref> Former [[Chief Minister of the Northern Territory|Chief Minister]] and Territory Alliance Leader [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]] claimed to have replaced her as Opposition Leader on 18 March 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.ntnews.com.au/news/northern-territory/robyn-lambley-joins-terry-mills-territory-alliance-sets-up-almighty-clp-showdown/news-story/b1a09c5f1a7595e96d222b9357b1435e|title = Territory Alliance says it has taken NT Opposition status|accessdate = 24 Mar 2020}}</ref> however this claim was not formalised by the Legislative Assembly.\n\nOn 24 March, Finocchiaro raised a motion under standing orders which allowed the assembly to decide on the opposition party, with the CLP winning opposition status by 5 votes to 3.<ref name=\"oppreturn\">{{cite news |last1=Aikman |first1=Amos |title=NT parliament again resolves that opposition should change |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/nation/politics/nt-parliament-again-resolves-that-opposition-should-change/news-story/2823fe70c6fe243189d84425474e5708 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The Australian |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFinocchiaro is married to Sam Burke, the son of former NT chief minister [[Denis Burke (Australian politician)|Denis Burke]]. She is of Italian descent and has been \"heavily involved in the NT's Italian community\",<ref name=ABCprofile/> including as CEO of the Italian Festival Association of the Northern Territory.<ref name=stories/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.countryliberals.org.au/members.php?id=42 Lia Finocchiaro \u2013 Candidate for Drysdale (Country Liberal Party)]\n*{{Twitter}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-nt}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ross Bohlin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral division of Drysdale|Drysdale]]|years=2012\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Eva Lawler]]}}\n{{s-new|seat}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral division of Spillett|Spillett]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gary Higgins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2020}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lynne Walker (politician)|Lynne Walker]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= Deputy [[Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2016\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gary Higgins]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gary Higgins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Country Liberal Party]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Styles]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= Deputy Leader of the [[Country Liberal Party]]|years=2016\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Gary Higgins]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NTCurrentMPs}}\n{{Leaders of the Country Liberal Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finocchiaro, Lia}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Country Liberal Party members of the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition in the Northern Territory]]\n[[Category:Australian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Adelaide Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Charles Darwin University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]]\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Peter Styles\u2192Peter Styles (politician)(2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lia_Finocchiaro"}
{"title_page": "Victoria Schuck Award", "text_new": "{{Infobox award\n| name             = Victoria Schuck Award\n| subheader        = <!-- or | current_awards = -->\n| image            = \n| image_size       = <!-- or | image_upright = -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| description      = Best book on women and politics\n| sponsor          = [[American Political Science Association]]\n| date             = <!-- {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location         = <!-- or | venue = or | site = -->\n| country          = \n| presenter        = \n| host             = <!-- or | hosts = -->\n| former name      = \n| preshow_host     = \n| acts             = \n| reward           = \n| year             = \n| year2            = \n| holder_label     = \n| holder           = <!-- or | winner = or | winners = -->\n| most_awards      = <!-- or | most_wins = -->\n| most_nominations = \n| award1_type      = \n| award1_winner    = \n| award2_type      = \n| award2_winner    = \n| award3_type      = \n| award3_winner    = \n| award4_type      = \n| award4_winner    = \n| award5_type      = \n| award5_winner    = \n| website          = https://www.apsanet.org/PROGRAMS/APSA-Awards/Victoria-Schuck-Award\n| network          = <!-- or | network_list = -->\n| runtime          = \n| viewership       = <!-- or | ratings = -->\n| producer         = \n| director         = \n| image2           = \n| image2size       = <!-- or | image_upright2 -->\n| alt2             = \n| caption2         = \n| precedence_label = \n| individual       = \n| higher           = \n| same             = \n| lower            = \n| related          = \n| previous         = \n| main             = \n| next             = \n}}\nThe Victoria Schuck Award is an annual prize granted by the [[American Political Science Association]] to the author of the best book published in the previous year on the topic of on women and politics.<ref name=apsa>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/PROGRAMS/APSA-Awards/Victoria-Schuck-Award |title=Victoria Schuck Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2018 |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> The award is named in honor of the political scientist [[Victoria Schuck]]. Although a number of area-specific sections of the American Political Science Association have dedicated book awards, the Schuck Award is one of only a few awards given directly by the Association rather than by a subsection of it.<ref name=str>{{cite journal |first=Sue |last=Tolleson-Rinehart |title=The Victoria Schuck Award: A Sonata for Gender Politics Scholarship |journal=[[Politics & Gender]] |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=294\u2013302 |date=6 June 2011 |doi=10.1017/S1743923X11000146}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe prize was established in 1986 by the American Political Science Association's Executive Director Thomas Mann, its President Aaron Wildavsky, and its Executive Council, at the urging of Victoria Schuck.<ref name=str/> It was originally endowed by Schuck at a value of $500 per award, out of a fund that she donated totaling $3000.<ref name=str/> By 2020 the award carried a prize of $750.<ref name=apsa/>\n\nThe committee that awards the prize consists of political scientists who are members of the American Political Science Association; the first prize was awarded by [[Susan J. Carroll]], [[Jean Bethke Elshtain]], and Norma Noonan.<ref name=str/>\n\n==Past winners==\nThe past recipients of the prize in each year are as follows:\n* 1988\u00a0[[Rebecca E. Klatch]], ''Women of the new right''\n* 1988 [[Jane Mansbridge]], ''Why we lost the ERA''<ref name=mns>{{cite web |title=Victoria Schuck Award Winners |url=http://web.mnstate.edu/schwartz/AmerPoliSciAssocSchuck.html |publisher=Minnesota State University |year=2018 |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 1989\u00a0[[Zillah R. Eisenstein]], ''The female body and the law''\n* 1989 [[Carole Pateman]], ''The sexual contract''<ref name=mns/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/polisci/faculty/pateman/CV.html |title=Carole Pateman CV |publisher=University of California, Los Angeles |year=2011 |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 1990 [[Susan Moller Okin]], ''Justice, gender and the family''\n* 1990 [[Judith Stiehm]], ''Arms and the enlisted woman''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1991 [[Donald G. Mathews]], ''Sex, gender, and the politics of ERA : a state and the nation''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1991 [[Iris M. Young]], ''Sex, Gender, and the Politics of Sex: A State and a Nation''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://gradschool.duke.edu/about/news/feminist-historian-de-hart-receive-2019-distinguished-alumni-award |title=Feminist Historian De Hart to Receive 2019 Distinguished Alumni Award |date=18 April 2019 |work=Duke Graduate School News |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 1992\u00a0[[Nancy Caraway]], ''Segregated sisterhood: racism and the politics of American feminism''\n* 1992 [[Anne Phillips]], ''Engendering democracy''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1993\u00a0[[Virginia Sapiro]], ''A vindication of political virtue: the political theory of Mary Wollstonecraft''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1994\u00a0[[Cynthia R. Daniels]], ''At women's expense: state power and the politics of fetal rights''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1995\u00a0[[Barbara J. Nelson]] and [[Najma Chowdhury]], ''Women and politics worldwide''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1996\u00a0[[Gwendolyn Mink]], ''The wages of motherhood: inequality in the welfare state, 1917-1942''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1997\u00a0[[Kristi Anderson]], ''After suffrage: women in partisan and electoral politics before the New Deal''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1998\u00a0[[Uma Narayan]], ''Dislocating cultures: identities, traditions, and Third-World feminism''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1999\u00a0[[Mary Fainsod Katzenstein]], ''Faithful and fearless: moving feminist protest inside the church and military''<ref name=mns/>\n* 2000\u00a0[[Judith A. Baer]], ''Our lives before the law: constructing a feminist jurisprudence''<ref name=mns/>\n* 2001\u00a0[[Jean Reith Schroedel]], ''Is the fetus a person? A comparison of policies across the fifty states''<ref name=mns/>\n* 2001 [[Aili Mari Tripp]], ''Women & politics in Uganda''<ref name=mns/>\n* 2002 [[Sidney Verba]], [[Kay Lehman Schlozman]], and [[Nancy Burns]], ''The private roots of public action: gender, equality, and political participation''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bc.edu/bc-web/bcnews/campus-community/honors/schlozman-wins-miller-prize.html |title=Outstanding career achievement |date=8 September 2018 |work=Boston College News |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2002 [[Joshua S. Goldstein]], ''War and gender: how gender shapes the war system and vice versa''<ref name=mns/>\n* 2003\u00a0[[Louise Chappell]], ''Gendering Government: Feminist Engagement with the State in Australia and Canada''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2004\u00a0[[Nancy J. Hirschmann]], ''Subject of Liberty: Toward a Feminist Theory of Freedom''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2005\u00a0[[Saba Mahmood]], ''Politics of Piety: The Islamic Revival and the Feminist Subject''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/28/us/saba-mahmood-dead.html |title=Saba Mahmood, 57, Dies; Traced Intersection of Feminism and Islam |date=28 March 2018 |work=The New York Times |last=Salam |first=Maya |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2006\u00a0[[Valentine M. Moghadam]], ''Globalizing Women: Transnational Feminist Networks''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thecairoreview.com/contributors/valentine-m-moghadam/ |title=Valentine M. Moghadam |year=2018 |work=The Cairo Review |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2007\u00a0[[Shireen Hassim]], ''Women's Organizations and Democracy in South Africa: Contesting Authority''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2007 [[Kathrin S. Zippel]], ''The Politics of Sexual Harassment: A Comparative Study of the United States, the European Union, and Germany''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2008\u00a0[[Georgina Waylen]], ''Engendering Transitions: Women\u2019s Mobilization, Institutions, and Gender Outcomes''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2008 [[Anna Marie Smith]], ''Welfare Reform and Sexual Regulation''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2009\u00a0[[Kristin Bumiller]], ''In an Abusive State: How Neoliberalism Appropriated the Feminist Movement Against Sexual Violence''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2010\u00a0[[Mona Lena Krook]], ''Quotas for Women in Politics: Gender and Candidate Selection Reform Worldwide''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2011\u00a0[[Torben Iversen]] and [[Frances Rosenbluth]], ''Women, Work & Politics: The Political Economy of Gender Inequality''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2012\u00a0[[S. Laurel Weldon]], ''When Protest Makes Policy: How Social Movements Represent Disadvantages Groups''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2013\u00a0[[Myra Marx Ferree]], ''Varieties of Feminism: German Gender Politics in Global Perspective''<ref name=sup>{{cite web |url=https://www.sup.org/books/awards/?award=Victoria%20Schuck%20Award |title=Titles recognized with Victoria Schuck Award |publisher=Stanford University Press |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2014\u00a0[[Deborah Jordan Brooks]], ''He Runs, She Runs: Why Gender Stereotypes Do Not Harm Women Candidates''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2015\u00a0[[Lisa Baldez]], ''Defying Convention: U.S. Resistance to the U.N. Treaty on Women's Rights''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2016\u00a0[[Sarah Deer]], ''The Beginning and End of Rape: Confronting Sexual Violence in Native America''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2017\u00a0[[J. Kevin Corder]] and [[Christina Wolbrecht]], ''Counting Women's Ballots: Female voters from Suffrage to through the New Deal''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2018\u00a0[[Kara Ellerby]], ''No Shortcut to Change: An Unlikely Path to a More Gender Equitable World''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2019 [[Brooke Ackerly]], ''Just Responsibility: A Human Rights Theory of Global Justice''<ref name=apsa/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox award\n| name             = Victoria Schuck Award\n| subheader        = <!-- or | current_awards = -->\n| image            = \n| image_size       = <!-- or | image_upright = -->\n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| description      = Best book on women and politics\n| sponsor          = [[American Political Science Association]]\n| date             = <!-- {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location         = <!-- or | venue = or | site = -->\n| country          = \n| presenter        = \n| host             = <!-- or | hosts = -->\n| former name      = \n| preshow_host     = \n| acts             = \n| reward           = \n| year             = \n| year2            = \n| holder_label     = \n| holder           = <!-- or | winner = or | winners = -->\n| most_awards      = <!-- or | most_wins = -->\n| most_nominations = \n| award1_type      = \n| award1_winner    = \n| award2_type      = \n| award2_winner    = \n| award3_type      = \n| award3_winner    = \n| award4_type      = \n| award4_winner    = \n| award5_type      = \n| award5_winner    = \n| website          = https://www.apsanet.org/PROGRAMS/APSA-Awards/Victoria-Schuck-Award\n| network          = <!-- or | network_list = -->\n| runtime          = \n| viewership       = <!-- or | ratings = -->\n| producer         = \n| director         = \n| image2           = \n| image2size       = <!-- or | image_upright2 -->\n| alt2             = \n| caption2         = \n| precedence_label = \n| individual       = \n| higher           = \n| same             = \n| lower            = \n| related          = \n| previous         = \n| main             = \n| next             = \n}}\nThe Victoria Schuck Award is an annual prize granted by the [[American Political Science Association]] to the author of the best book published in the previous year on the topic of on women and politics.<ref name=apsa>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/PROGRAMS/APSA-Awards/Victoria-Schuck-Award |title=Victoria Schuck Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2018 |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> The award is named in honor of the political scientist [[Victoria Schuck]]. Although a number of area-specific sections of the American Political Science Association have dedicated book awards, the Schuck Award is one of only a few awards given directly by the Association rather than by a subsection of it.<ref name=str>{{cite journal |first=Sue |last=Tolleson-Rinehart |title=The Victoria Schuck Award: A Sonata for Gender Politics Scholarship |journal=[[Politics & Gender]] |volume=7 |issue=2 |pages=294\u2013302 |date=6 June 2011 |doi=10.1017/S1743923X11000146}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe prize was established in 1986 by the American Political Science Association's Executive Director Thomas Mann, its President Aaron Wildavsky, and its Executive Council, at the urging of Victoria Schuck.<ref name=str/> It was originally endowed by Schuck at a value of $500 per award, out of a fund that she donated totaling $3000.<ref name=str/> By 2020 the award carried a prize of $750.<ref name=apsa/>\n\nThe committee that awards the prize consists of political scientists who are members of the American Political Science Association; the first prize was awarded by [[Susan J. Carroll]], [[Jean Bethke Elshtain]], and Norma Noonan.<ref name=str/>\n\n==Past winners==\nThe past recipients of the prize in each year are as follows:\n* 1988\u00a0[[Rebecca E. Klatch]], ''Women of the new right''\n* 1988 [[Jane Mansbridge]], ''Why we lost the ERA''<ref name=mns>{{cite web |title=Victoria Schuck Award Winners |url=http://web.mnstate.edu/schwartz/AmerPoliSciAssocSchuck.html |publisher=Minnesota State University |year=2018 |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 1989\u00a0[[Zillah R. Eisenstein]], ''The female body and the law''\n* 1989 [[Carole Pateman]], ''The sexual contract''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1990 [[Susan Moller Okin]], ''Justice, gender and the family''\n* 1990 [[Judith Stiehm]], ''Arms and the enlisted woman''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1991 [[Donald G. Mathews]], ''Sex, gender, and the politics of ERA : a state and the nation''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1991 [[Iris M. Young]], ''Sex, Gender, and the Politics of Sex: A State and a Nation''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://gradschool.duke.edu/about/news/feminist-historian-de-hart-receive-2019-distinguished-alumni-award |title=Feminist Historian De Hart to Receive 2019 Distinguished Alumni Award |date=18 April 2019 |work=Duke Graduate School News |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 1992\u00a0[[Nancy Caraway]], ''Segregated sisterhood: racism and the politics of American feminism''\n* 1992 [[Anne Phillips]], ''Engendering democracy''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1993\u00a0[[Virginia Sapiro]], ''A vindication of political virtue: the political theory of Mary Wollstonecraft''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1994\u00a0[[Cynthia R. Daniels]], ''At women's expense: state power and the politics of fetal rights''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1995\u00a0[[Barbara J. Nelson]] and [[Najma Chowdhury]], ''Women and politics worldwide''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1996\u00a0[[Gwendolyn Mink]], ''The wages of motherhood: inequality in the welfare state, 1917-1942''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1997\u00a0[[Kristi Anderson]], ''After suffrage: women in partisan and electoral politics before the New Deal''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1998\u00a0[[Uma Narayan]], ''Dislocating cultures: identities, traditions, and Third-World feminism''<ref name=mns/>\n* 1999\u00a0[[Mary Fainsod Katzenstein]], ''Faithful and fearless: moving feminist protest inside the church and military''<ref name=mns/>\n* 2000\u00a0[[Judith A. Baer]], ''Our lives before the law: constructing a feminist jurisprudence''<ref name=mns/>\n* 2001\u00a0[[Jean Reith Schroedel]], ''Is the fetus a person? A comparison of policies across the fifty states''<ref name=mns/>\n* 2001 [[Aili Mari Tripp]], ''Women & politics in Uganda''<ref name=mns/>\n* 2002 [[Sidney Verba]], [[Kay Lehman Schlozman]], and [[Nancy Burns]], ''The private roots of public action: gender, equality, and political participation''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bc.edu/bc-web/bcnews/campus-community/honors/schlozman-wins-miller-prize.html |title=Outstanding career achievement |date=8 September 2018 |work=Boston College News |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2002 [[Joshua S. Goldstein]], ''War and gender: how gender shapes the war system and vice versa''<ref name=mns/>\n* 2003\u00a0[[Louise Chappell]], ''Gendering Government: Feminist Engagement with the State in Australia and Canada''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2004\u00a0[[Nancy J. Hirschmann]], ''Subject of Liberty: Toward a Feminist Theory of Freedom''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2005\u00a0[[Saba Mahmood]], ''Politics of Piety: The Islamic Revival and the Feminist Subject''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/28/us/saba-mahmood-dead.html |title=Saba Mahmood, 57, Dies; Traced Intersection of Feminism and Islam |date=28 March 2018 |work=The New York Times |last=Salam |first=Maya |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2006\u00a0[[Valentine M. Moghadam]], ''Globalizing Women: Transnational Feminist Networks''<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thecairoreview.com/contributors/valentine-m-moghadam/ |title=Valentine M. Moghadam |year=2018 |work=The Cairo Review |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2007\u00a0[[Shireen Hassim]], ''Women's Organizations and Democracy in South Africa: Contesting Authority''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2007 [[Kathrin S. Zippel]], ''The Politics of Sexual Harassment: A Comparative Study of the United States, the European Union, and Germany''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2008\u00a0[[Georgina Waylen]], ''Engendering Transitions: Women\u2019s Mobilization, Institutions, and Gender Outcomes''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2008 [[Anna Marie Smith]], ''Welfare Reform and Sexual Regulation''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2009\u00a0[[Kristin Bumiller]], ''In an Abusive State: How Neoliberalism Appropriated the Feminist Movement Against Sexual Violence''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2010\u00a0[[Mona Lena Krook]], ''Quotas for Women in Politics: Gender and Candidate Selection Reform Worldwide''<ref name=apsa/>\n* 2011\u00a0[[Torben Iversen]] and [[Frances Rosenbluth]], ''Women, Work & Politics: The Political Economy of Gender Inequality''<ref name=apsa/>\n*